@node Installation via @code{package-vc-selected-packages}
@subsection Installation via @code{package-vc-selected-packages}

In your Emacs session, load @code{package-vc} and add entries to @code{package-vc-selected-packages}.  Install the selected packages by typing @samp{M-x package-vc-install-selected-packages RET}.  Finally, make the package selection permanent in your Emacs initialization file too:

@lisp
(require 'package-vc)

(add-to-list 'package-vc-selected-packages
             '(nael
               :url "https://codeberg.org/mekeor/nael.git"
               :lisp-dir "nael"))

;; Optional:

;; (add-to-list 'package-vc-selected-packages
;;              '(nael-markdown
;;                :url "https://codeberg.org/mekeor/nael.git"
;;                :lisp-dir "nael-markdown"))

;; (add-to-list 'package-vc-selected-packages
;;              '(nael-lsp
;;                :url "https://codeberg.org/mekeor/nael.git"
;;                :lisp-dir "nael-lsp"))

;; Call `package-vc-install-selected-packages' whenever modifying the
;; list of selected package recipes.

(package-initialize)
@end lisp

@node Installation via @code{use-package} @samp{vc}
@subsection Installation via @code{use-package} @samp{:vc}

Since version 30 from 2025, Emacs' popular @code{use-package} macro features the @samp{:vc} keyword as interface to @code{package-vc}.

(Because each package has autoload-cookies on relevant expressions, and because @code{use-package} will load each package's @samp{*-autoloads.el} file that is generated at installation, you don't need to specify load-triggers like @samp{:mode}.)

@lisp
(use-package nael
  :vc ( :url "https://codeberg.org/mekeor/nael.git"
        :lisp-dir "nael"))

;; Optional:

;; (use-package nael-markdown
;;   :after markdown-mode
;;   :vc ( :url "https://codeberg.org/mekeor/nael.git"
;;         :lisp-dir "nael-markdown"))

;; (use-package nael-lsp
;;   :after nael
;;   :vc ( :url "https://codeberg.org/mekeor/nael.git"
;;         :lisp-dir "nael-lsp"))
@end lisp

@node Usage
@chapter Usage

Language Server Protocol (LSP):

@itemize
@item
To start an LSP client automatically, configure @code{nael-mode-hook}.  To start one interactively, type @samp{C-c C-e} (@code{eglot}), or, if you have installed @code{nael-lsp}, @samp{C-c C-l} (@code{lsp}).

@item
@samp{C-h .} (@code{eldoc-doc-buffer}) displays the ElDoc documentation buffer showing tactic state and expected goal at point.
@end itemize

Abbreviations:

@itemize
@item
To enable abbreviations automatically, configure @code{nael-mode-hook}.  To enable them interactively, type @samp{C-c C-a} (@code{abbrev-mode}).

@item
@samp{C-c C-k} (@code{nael-abbrev-help}) will tell you how the abbreviation for the active region or character at point.

@item
Note that Nael's Abbrev tables use the @samp{:regexp} property which @uref{https://github.com/minad/cape/discussions/158#discussioncomment-14687758, is} neither compatible with Company nor Cape.  For completion at point, @code{nael-abbrev} defines @code{nael-abbrev-capf} which is buffer-locally added to @code{completion-at-point-functions} whenever Abbrev mode is enabled inside Nael.  To ditch this CAPF, set the @code{nael-abbrev-capf} variable to @samp{nil}.
@end itemize

Emacs commands beyond Nael:

@itemize
@item
@samp{C-c C-c} or equally @samp{C-x p c} (@code{project-compile}) suggests @samp{lake build} as command to build the current project.
@item
@samp{M-g i} (@code{imenu}) jumps to a interactively chosen definition in current buffer.
@item
@samp{M-;} (@code{comment-dwim}) will toggle active region as comment or, if no region is active, create a comment at end of line.
@item
@samp{M-q} (@code{prog-fill-reindent-defun}) will fill the string- or comment-paragraph at point, or reindent the point-surrounding code.
@end itemize

